pgTitle: List of The Brady Bunch episodes

rows.text: Jan's allergies are acting up, so Carol keeps her home from school. Alice and Carol are worried, and Alice fears it might be Mike or one of the boys. When it seems that Jan is allergic to Tiger, the family fear they might have to lose their pet dog, until it is learned that Jan is only allergic to his new flea powder.

After Cindy and Bobby get mad at each other, Cindy loses her doll. She accuses Bobby of "doll-napping". Bobby promises that he didn't take it, but this is not enough for Cindy. Bobby realizes that Cindy is very sad, and he spends all of his money on a new doll for her, but she won't accept it. Clues lead to the real culprit: Tiger.

Marcia and Greg compete for class president. Partisanship overtakes the household, prompting Mike to step in and lecture the kids about unity. It's a talk Greg takes very seriously, particularly when his campaign manager Rusty (Stephen Liss) suggests stirring up rumors about Marcia. Greg rejects Rusty's suggestion and fires him. Marcia overhears this and realizes Greg has integrity and a sense of fair play, and decides to concede to Greg.

"Is There a Doctor in the House?"

Marcia nominates Mike as "Father of the Year" in a newspaper contest. Her actions to keep this secret results in several misunderstandings. She is first asked to do a few extra chores for being caught in Mike's den. After not doing them to write this letter secretly, she is then grounded for a week. Then when she sees the deadline for entry for the contest was the next day she sneaks out to mail the letter. When she's caught outside well past her bedtime she is being grounded from going with the family on a ski trip which was being planned in the subplot. Things are resolved when Mike is presented with a "Father of the Year" plaque.

When Jan becomes depressed from a lack of attention, her spirits are lifted when she receives a locket from a secret admirer, however Jan loses the locket. Jan uses her detective skills to find it, and can't discover who sent it. Alice later confides in Jan that she sent the locket; she was a middle child too and often felt inferior to her two sisters.
